## M22.1(2/8): bare `@x` pin sigil is rejected in V1.
##
## Per GPT-5.5 entry 39 (M22.1 "fake-surface audit"): the M19/M21
## ownership grid included `@x` as a pin sigil, but pinning was
## explicitly deferred to V2 — emit was a semantic no-op (`@x`
## lowered to plain `x`). A sigil with no enforced semantics is
## exactly the "fake surface" Rig is supposed to avoid; it
## promises a guarantee the compiler does not deliver.
##
## V1 policy: reject `(pin <expr>)` at sema time with a clear
## "reserved for V2" diagnostic. The lexer still classifies `@x`
## as a pin prefix (so `@x` vs `@len(x)` disambiguation works),
## but the resulting IR is rejected. When V2 grows real
## pinning/stable-address semantics, this sigil is the natural
## spelling — preserving the lexer tokenization keeps the design
## space open without keeping the false promise.
##
## The `@builtin(...)` form is unaffected: `@sizeOf(T)`,
## `@TypeOf(x)`, etc. go through the `builtin` IR tag (separate
## parse path), not `pin`.

sub main()
  x = 42
  p = @x             # error: pinning sigil reserved for V2
  print(p)
